rd in the Beacon's keening.\",\n        \"Climb the lower galleries of the Beacon of Myr Sal with a lens-tender to listen to its residual hums for clues.\"\n      ],\n      \"dialogue\": [\n        {\"speaker\": \"Isha Brinehand\", \"lines\": \"You hear that, Tairn? The Beacon shouldn’t sing when the sky is clean and the gulls are lazy; it only does that when a storm cheats the horizon or a lie big enough to tax the sea has been told where the city can hear it. I’ve got three kids swinging over black water on a chain that thinks it is the tongue of a bell, and I’ll not lose a hand today to a jam that reminds the city of my worst morning. Take your hook, take two steady souls, and make that lift remember it’s a ladder and not a gallows; wedge, counter, breathe with the tide, and don’t let panic write the last line. Bring them home with their fingers and names intact, then put your ears to what the glass left hanging in the air because I swear that keen ran through the House of Weights like a thin blade and tasted of oaths. Keep your eyes open up the stacks, too; when glass hums like this somebody’s tuning, and the Conclave has more forks than I have patience, and House Saltvein loves a quiet cord that moves a gate.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Tairn Latch\", \"lines\": \"I hear it all the way down my teeth, Foreman—like a word that didn’t want to be said and cracked on its way out. I’ll take the hook and a wedge-board, and I’ll count my breaths by the chain’s click until it listens, and I’ll come back up with three more souls cussing me for bruises instead of being etched on a salt stele under Lost. The Beacon’s cry rode my scars like it knew the path already; I’ll follow the echo down the catwalks and up into the glass if the gate-keepers at the Prismarium will let a docker’s boots touch their steps. I’ll speak clean to the Wardens at Windward Bastion with whatever I can hear in the hum, because if pirates smell fear across the Veiled Current we’ll all be counting b